title=\"Solve a workplace dispute\">solve a workplace dispute</a> about what is unreasonable.</p>\n\n<p>Employees without a mobility clause in their contract can choose whether or not to move. </p>\n\n<h2>Redundancy</h2>\n\n<p>Employers can make their employees <a href=\"/redundant-your-rights\" title=\"Redundancy: your rights\">redundant</a> if they decide not to move. </p>\n\n<p>Employees may have a right to redundancy pay if:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>they match the <a href=\"/redundant-your-rights\" title=\"Redundancy: your rights\">redundancy criteria</a> - eg they&rsquo;ve worked for the employer for a certain amount of time</li>\n  <li>they&rsquo;re not getting any compensation from their employer because they decided not to move</li>\n  <li>they haven’t ‘unreasonably’ refused an offer of suitable alternative work </li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>‘Unreasonable’ could mean refusing to move even though the new location is nearby and the employee could drive or easily take public transport. </p>\n\n<p>However, it may be reasonable to say no if it involves a difficult journey or affects personal matters like children&rsquo;s education.</p>\n\n<h2>Compensation</h2>\n<p>Employers don&rsquo;t have to offer employees any compensation for relocating, unless it&rsquo;s specified in their contract. </p>\n\n<h2>Disputes</h2>\n\n<p>Employers and employees may have to <a href=\"/solve-workplace-dispute\" title=\"Solve a workplace dispute\">solve a dispute</a> over issues with relocation, eg if they think someone is being unreasonable and refuse them a redundancy payment.</p>\n\n<h2>If an employer is taken over</h2>\n\n<p>If an employer is taken over and the new owners want to relocate, employees&rsquo; rights are protected by certain regulations. These are known as <a href=\"/transfers-takeovers/overview\" title=\"Business transfers, takeovers and TUPE\">TUPE - Transfer of Undertakings Protection of Employment</a>.</p>\n\n<p>All employee&rsquo;s existing rights, including contractual rights and redundancy protection, stay the same. It makes no difference that it&rsquo;s a new owner that introduces the relocation.</p>\n","alternative_title":"Employee rights when employers relocate"},"tags":[{"title":"Contracts of employment and working hours","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/tags/employing-people%2Fcontracts.json","web_url":null,"details":{"description":"Includes types of worker, employee rights, overtime and changes to contracts","short_description":null,"type":"section"},"content_with_tag":{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/with_tag.json?tag=employing-people%2Fcontracts","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/browse/employing-people/contracts"},"parent":{"title":"Employing people","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/tags/employing-people.json","web_url":null,"details":{"description":"Includes pay, contracts and hiring","short_description":null,"type":"section"},"content_with_tag":{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/with_tag.json?tag=employing-people","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/browse/employing-people"},"parent":null}},{"title":"Your contract and working hours","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/tags/working%2Fcontract-working-hours.json","web_url":null,"details":{"description":"Includes employment status, workers' rights and changes to contracts","short_description":null,"type":"section"},"content_with_tag":{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/with_tag.json?tag=working%2Fcontract-working-hours","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/browse/working/contract-working-hours"},"parent":{"title":"Working, jobs and pensions","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/tags/working.json","web_url":null,"details":{"description":"Includes holidays and finding a job","short_description":null,"type":"section"},"content_with_tag":{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/with_tag.json?tag=working","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/browse/working"},"parent":null}}],"related":[{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/employment-contracts-and-conditions.json","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/employment-contracts-and-conditions","title":"Employment contracts","fo