ice - in some circumstances</li>\n  <li>in security and surveillance</li>\n  <li>as a domestic servant in a private household  </li>\n  <li>where 24-hour staffing is required</li>\n  <li>certain categories of seafarers, sea-fishermen and workers on vessels on inland waterways</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Other work sectors might have different rules on maximum working hours and workers should always speak to their employer.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>If you’re a trainee doctor the 48-hour maximum working hours rule applies to you, <a href=\"calculating-your-working-hours\" title=\"Calculating your working hours\">averaged over 26 weeks</a>.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Opting out of the 48-hour week</h2>\n\n<p>Workers 18 or over who want to work more than 48 hours a week, can choose to opt out of the 48-hour limit. </p>\n\n<p>This could be for a certain period or indefinitely. It must be voluntary and in writing.</p>\n\n<p>It can&rsquo;t be contained in an agreement with the whole workforce. However, employers are allowed to ask individual workers if they&rsquo;d be willing to opt out.</p>\n\n<p>An employer shouldn&rsquo;t sack or unfairly treat a worker (eg refused promotion) for refusing to sign an opt-out.</p>\n\n<h3>Workers who can&rsquo;t opt out</h3>\n\n<p>Employers must not allow the following staff to opt out:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>workers in the road transport industry, eg delivery drivers</li>\n  <li>workers on ships or boats</li>\n  <li>airline staff</li>\n  <li>other staff who travel in and operate vehicles covered by EU rules on drivers’ hours, eg bus conductors</li>\n  <li>security guards on a vehicle carrying high-value goods</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Cancelling an opt-out agreement</h3>\n<p>A worker can cancel their opt-out agreement whenever they want - even if it&rsquo;s part of their employment contract.</p>\n\n<p>They must give their employer at least 7 days&rsquo; notice. This could be longer (up to 3 months) if the worker previously agreed this in the written opt-out agreement with the employer.</p>\n\n<p>The employer isn&rsquo;t allowed to force a worker to cancel their opt-out agreement.</p>\n\n<div class=\"example\">\n<p><strong>Example of opt-out agreement:</strong></p>\n\n<p>I [worker&rsquo;s name] agree that I may work for more than an average of 48 hours a week. If I change my mind, I will give my employer [amount of time - up to 3 months&rsquo;] notice in writing to end this agreement.\nSigned……&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;\nDated………&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>16 and 17 year olds</h2>\n\n<p>16 and 17 year olds can&rsquo;t normally work more than 8 hours a day or 40 hours a week.</p>\n\n<p>The hours can&rsquo;t be averaged out for 16 and 17 year olds. There is also no opt-out which means that they can&rsquo;t work longer hours even if they want to.</p>\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/maximum-weekly-working-hours/calculating-your-working-hours","slug":"calculating-your-working-hours","order":3,"title":"Calculating your working hours","body":"<p>Only certain hours count as work when weekly hours are calculated.</p>\n\n<h2>What counts as work</h2>\n\n<p>As well as doing the normal duties, a working week includes:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>job-related training</li>\n  <li>job-related travelling time, eg sales reps</li>\n  <li>working lunches, eg business lunches</li>\n  <li>time spent actually working abroad in some cases</li>\n  <li>paid and some unpaid overtime</li>\n  <li>time spent on call at the workplace</li>\n  <li>any other time that is treated as &lsquo;working time&rsquo; under a contract </li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>What doesn&rsquo;t count as work</h2>\n\n<p>A working week doesn&rsquo;t include:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>breaks when no work is done, eg lunch breaks</li>\n  <li>normal travel to and from work</li>\n  <li>time on call away from the workplace</li>\n  <li>evening and day-release classes not related to work</li>\n  <li>travelling outside of normal working hours</li>\n  <li>unpaid overtime a worker has volunteered for, eg staying late to finish something off</li>\n  <li>paid or unpaid holiday</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Time used to calculate average hours</h2>\n\n<p>The average working hours are calculated over a &lsquo;reference&rsquo; period. This is normally a 17-week period. </p>\n\n<p>Someone can work more than 48 hours in 1 week, so long as the average over 17 weeks  is less than 48 hours a week.</p>\n\n<p>Some jobs have different reference periods:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>doctors in training have a 26-week reference period  </li>\n  <li>the offshore sector has a 52-week reference period  </li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>Days when a worker is off (eg paid leave, time off sick) don’t count towards the reference period.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Working hours if someone has more than one job</h2>\n\n<p>If someone works for more than one employer, the amount of combined hours shouldn&rsquo;t be more than 48 hours on average a week.</p>\n\n<p>Workers with more than one job could either:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>consider signing an opt-out agreement if their total time worked is more than 48 hours</li>\n  <li>reduce their hours to meet the 48-hour limit</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/maximum-weekly-working-hours/help-and-advice","slug":"help-and-advice","order":4,"title":"Help and advice","body":"<p>For free and confidential advice on working hours workers can contact the Pay and Work Rights Helpline.</p>\n\n<div class=\"contact\">\n<p><strong>Pay and Work Rights Helpline</strong>  </p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://payandworkrights.direct.gov.uk/\" title=\"Pay and Work Rights general enquiry form\" rel=\"external\">Enquiry form</a><br />\n<a href=\"https://payandworkrights.direct.gov.uk/complaints/\" title=\"Pay and Work Rights complaint form\" rel=\"external\">Complaint form</a><br />\n<strong>T