 likely that they&rsquo;ll work a proportion of their annual working time during the night</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The rules about how long staff work at night are based on <a href=\"/maximum-weekly-working-hours/calculating-your-working-hours\" title=\"calculating working hours\">average working time</a>, which is usually calculated over a 17-week period. This includes regular overtime but not occasional overtime.</p>\n\n<p>If the workers and the employer both agree as part of a collective or workforce agreement, the working hours can be averaged over a longer period, eg up to 52 weeks.</p>\n\n<p>Employers must make sure that workers don&rsquo;t work more than an average of 8 hours in a 24-hour period. Workers can&rsquo;t opt out of this working limit.</p>\n\n<p>Employers must keep records of night workers&rsquo; working hours to prove they aren&rsquo;t exceeding night working limits. Employers must keep the records for at least 2 years.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice help-notice\">\n<p>Workers shouldn’t be <a href=\"/discrimination-your-rights\" title=\"Discrimination: your rights\">discriminated against</a> because they refuse to work nights.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Young workers and staff dealing with special hazards</h2>\n\n<p>Some workers must be treated differently:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>staff under 18 are not usually allowed to work at night - there are also <a href=\"/child-employment/restrictions-on-child-employment\" title=\"employing staff under 18\">other restrictions</a> on when they can work</li>\n  <li>night workers who deal with special hazards or whose work involves mental or physical strain can&rsquo;t work longer than 8 hours in any 24-hour period</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>Special hazards and work involving mental or physical strain should be identified as part of <a href=\"http://www.hse.gov.uk/risk/faq.htm#q1\" title=\"Employer risk assessments\" rel=\"external\">risk assessments.</a> They may also be set out i