normal working week and breaks during the day. </p>\n\n<p>This is a minimum of 90 hours rest a week on average, but it may not be at normal times.</p>\n\n<p>Employers must also follow the general <a href=\"/maximum-weekly-working-hours\" title=\"rules on working hours\">rules on working hours</a>.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>If you’re not sure whether these exceptions apply in your situation, contact the <a href=\"/pay-and-work-rights-helpline\" title=\"Pay and work rights helpline\">pay and work rights helpline</a>.</p>\n</div>\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/night-working-hours/health-assessments","slug":"health-assessments","order":3,"title":"Health assessments","body":"<p>Workers must be offered a free health assessment before they become a night worker and on a regular basis after that. </p>\n\n<p>Employers can do this with a questionnaire to see if the worker is fit to work nights. They should ask a qualified health professional for help developing the questionnaire.</p>\n\n<div class=\"form-download\">\n<p><a href=\"http://www.businesslink.gov.uk/Employing_People_files/Health_questionnaire_to_assess_if_you_are_fit_to_w.doc\" title=\"Download 'Sample health questionnaire for night workers' (DOC, 105KB)\" rel=\"external\">Download ‘Sample health questionnaire for night workers’ (DOC, 105KB)</a></p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>The worker should also be offered a follow-up examination by a health professional if the employer is unsure they’re fit to be a night worker.</p>\n</div>\n\n<p>Employers must keep <a href=\"/data-protection-your-business/recruitment-managing-staff-records\" title=\"Managing staff records\">confidential</a> records of:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>night staff&rsquo;s health assessments (keep these for 2 years)</li>\n  <li>dates when staff were offered a health assessment (if they didn&rsquo;t want one)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Employers should also take into account that night work might in